        Buddy says, "Oh! Right! You are! This is… outside my usual parameters. Um—"

        Buddy says, "Should you… talk to a trusted adult about your situation?"

        Despite the pain, the fear, the absolute chaos of my life right now—I laugh. It hurts my ribs but I can't help it.

        I say, "I'm the only adult here, Buddy."

        Buddy says, "Oh. Okay! Then we'll figure this out together! You're doing amazing, Kira!"

        I sit down heavily, medical supplies scattered around me while Buddy cheerfully narrates proper first aid procedures. This is what I've got: a kids' AI who thinks I need help tying my shoes—an AI designed to teach eight-year-olds about the water cycle, now responsible for keeping me alive on an alien planet.

        But Buddy *is* helping, in their own weird, overly educational way. After that awful silence, after losing SAM, having someone—something—in my head again… it's not nothing.

        I'm still alone—still hurt—still stranded on an unknown planet with no idea when rescue might come.

        But I'm alone with an overly cheerful AI who wants to turn my survival into a learning experience.

        I say, "Okay, Buddy."

        I open another medical kit, start cataloging what's usable, then say, "Let's figure out how to survive this—together."

